This book will attempt to explain the concept of renewable energy and give details of the various methods of harnessing renewable energy sources.
== Contents ==
#[[/About/]] this book #[[/Introduction/]] to Renewable Energy #[[/Bio Energy/]] #[[/Solar Thermal/]] #[[/Geothermal/]] #[[/Ocean Thermal/]] #[[/Wind/]] #[[/Hydro Energy/]] #[[/Solar Photovoltaic (PV)/]] #[[/Tidal Energy/]] #[[/Wave Energy/]] #[[/Energy Storage/]] :#[[/Chemical/]] :#[[/Mechanical/]] :#[[/Thermal Energy/]] #[[/More on Specific Renewable energy sources/]] :#[[/Biofuels/]] ::[[/Biofuel from Algae/]] ::[[/Biofuel from Land Based Plants/]] :[[/External Links/]] {{Subjects|Science}} {{Alphabetical|R}} {{status|0%}}

function glossary() {
  $j('div.glossary > dt').each( function() {
    var dt = $j(this), id = dt.children(':first-child').text().replace(/^\s+|\s+$/, "").replace(/\s+/g, "_");
    dt.before('<a id="'+id+'"></a>');
  }
}

$j(document).ready(glossary);

==Indenting and Line Length==

Use an indent of one tab (no spaces! good IDEs can convert this to pseudo spaces - 2 or 4 etc). If you use Emacs to edit your code,
you should set indent-tabs-mode to nil.  It  is  recommended  that  you  break
lines  at  approximately  75-85 characters.  There  is  no  standard  rule for 
the best way to break a line; use your judgement.  This applies to all file
types: PHP, HTML, CSS, Javascript, etc.

Indentation rules should be applied in the source file that will be edited
by others.  The visual appeal of HTML output should not be taken into
consideration when writing code that generates HTML.

==HTML Standards==

===Validation===

As of September 2006, the DocType on our documents will be XHTML 1.0
Transitional.  Therefore, compliant HTML according to the XHTML 1.0 standard
should be used at all times.  Exceptions should be just that.  A good
reference for the XHTML elements can be found at 
[http://www.devguru.com/Technologies/xhtml/quickref/xhtml_index.html DevGuru].

Also, to ensure that the box model is done correctly by IE 6, we must use the following DocType on all pages.  Only this doc type is to be used.  No other information should be placed before it.

{{Code:Basic|Example DocType|
<pre><!DOCTYPE html PUBLIC "-//W3C//DTD XHTML 1.0 Transitional//EN" "http://www.w3.org/TR/xhtml1/DTD/xhtml1-transitional.dtd"></pre>
}}

===Element Usage===

When at all possible, try and use standard HTML elements properly.  "Div Soup"
should be avoided at all times.  "Div Soup" refers to HTML where a div (or span)
is used when it is not needed.  For example, if you need a word to be bolded,
do not use a <tt>&lt;span&gt;</tt> tag and apply a style.  Instead, use the 
<tt>&lt;strong&gt;</tt> tag.

Tables should be used only when data needs to be displayed in columns.  One
cell tables should never be used. 

One common exception is needing to use <tt>&lt;div&gt;</tt> tags in place of
<tt>&lt;p&gt;</tt> tags when the contents of the tag will be other block level
elements such as <tt>&lt;ul&gt;</tt>.

{{Code:Basic|Example HTML|
<source lang="html4strict">
<div class="article">
    <h4>this is the headline</h4>
    <p>This is the body with an <strong>important word</strong>.</p>
    <small>Posted 2 days ago</small>
</div>
</source>
}}

==CSS Standards==

'''Inline styles should be avoided'''

Styles in CSS files should be as specific as possible.  One should always try
to avoid using a bare class name.  If you are styling an object that has a
container, your style should reference the continer as well as the element
being styled. The more verbose your styles in your CSS the less likely you
will mess up another element on another page accidentally.

The most efficient way to style an element is by styling that type of element
inside a container.  If only one element needs to be styled in a special way,
it should be assigned and id and styled using the id and preferably a container.


Here is some HTML from our sidebar:

{{Code:Basic|Example Article HTML|
<pre>
&lt;div id="sidebar"&gt;

    &lt;ul class="blue" id="categories"&gt;
        &lt;label&gt;&lt;a href="/categories/"&gt;Categories&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/label&gt;
        &lt;li class="current"&gt;&lt;a href="/categories/Computer/39.html"&gt;Computer&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
        &lt;li&gt;&lt;a href="/categories/Electronics/142.html"&gt;Electronics&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
